post_text:
Starting Monday, Food Service will add a fifth site for grab-and-go breakfasts and lunches. Families will be able to access FREE meals for children at Woodlawn Elementary from 11:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m. Monday-Friday (with weekend meals distributed Fridays).

Sites continuing to distribute meals are: Hillcrest Elementary, 11:30–1:00 p.m.; Kennedy Elementary, 11:30 a.m.- 12:30 p.m.; Sunflower Elementary, 12:30-1:30 p.m.; and Lawrence High, 4:30-5:45 p.m.

Adults may continue to pick up meals without children present at any of these sites. In order to comply with USDA requirements, they will be asked to list their children's names on a waiver and will receive a numbered piece of paper to display in their vehicle when picking up future meals. Thank you for assisting us with meeting these federal guidelines so we may continue offering free meals to children in our community.

post_text:
Friday night football. Same excitement. New safety rules:

*Two spectators per participant.
*Must be on guest lists to enter.
*Adults $7; K-12 Student $5. We ❤️ exact change.
*Gates open at 6:00; Games start at 7:00.
*Masks and 10 ft. social distancing required!
*No "walk-up" tickets sold.
*No student sections.
*No tailgating or congregating.
*No concessions sold.
*All spectators must remain in the stands.
*No standing on the tracks or going onto the fields.
*Exit promptly after the games.

We know: rules, rules, rules. They are for a good reason: the safety of players, coaches, staff, and fans. Please demonstrate good sportsmanship by following them.

Radio broadcasts: 92.9 FM The Bull (Free State); KLWN FM 101.7/AM 1320 (LHS).

Live streams: Uclicktv.com

Thank you for supporting our Chesty Lions and Firebirds!

It’s the news we have been waiting to hear: the USDA has announced that schools may apply to extend the free meals program. We can now continue to serve all children in the community (ages 1-18) FREE meals during the first six weeks of remote learning.

Starting September 8, grab-and-go meals will be available for pickup Monday-Friday (with weekend meals distributed Fridays) at these four school sites: Hillcrest Elementary, 12:00–1:00 p.m.; Kennedy Elementary, 11:30 a.m.- 12:30 p.m.; Sunflower Elementary, 12:30-1:30 p.m.; and Lawrence High, 4:30-5:45 p.m.

Due to the limited time federal funding may be available for free meals, it is still important that families submit updated free and reduced-price meal applications. Plus, families must apply for meal benefits to be eligible for waivers of school fees. Complete an application at https://www.myschoolapps.com/Application.

post_text: Superintendent Dr. Anthony Lewis announces that after continued conversations among the administration, the district has decided to allow athletic teams and activities to continue to compete for the next two weeks. The district will monitor public health data during this time and re-evaluate the metrics on September 10. The number of new COVID-19 cases has declined during each of the last two days. The administration wants to see if the spike in new positive cases driven by KU's entry testing continues to decline.

post_text: Firebirds' First Friends, a branch of National Honor Society headed-up by Amy Mai, and the other 2020-2021 National Honor Society Officers welcomed more than 30 new students (sophomores, juniors, and seniors) to Free State. Officers delivered welcome bags to the homes of each student. (They even drove to Ottawa for one delivery!) Welcome bags included Free State T-shirts donated by Student Council (Thank you, Mrs. Hayden!), along with many other goodies. The day ended with an online orientation including a video tour made by Mr. Lloyd and crew. Thank you to Amy McAnarney, Tina Mitchell, Lisa Koppes, Dena Johnston, Amanda Faunce, Katy Hayden, and Bryan Lloyd for your contributions. NHS Officers: Spencer Ware, president; Rebecca Feng, vice president; Audri Gutierrez, secretary, Asa Morrisson, director of communication; Ryan Malloy, director of activities; and Amy Mai, Firebirds' First Friends.

post_text: The school board authorized the administration to furlough Food Service staff as necessary given a decrease in the need for meals under a remote learning model and budget constraints. The district plans to notify 64 Food Service staff of the temporary action by letter. A self-sustaining program currently bringing in limited revenue to support labor and food costs, Food Service will use only the number of staff needed to provide meals for students during remote learning. Furloughed staff will continue to receive health benefits and may apply for unemployment. The district plans to bring back staff when students return to school buildings and regular meal service resumes.

post_text: I feel the earth move under my feet... and a new inclusive early childhood playground will soon materialize!
shared_text:
Lawrence Schools Foundation
August 21 at 6:22 PM ·

Construction is underway!

The William Dann Playtown

Did you know that an Early Childhood playground at Kennedy Elementary will soon becoming an inclusive playground for all children 2-5 years of age? Inclusive for children with mobility exceptionalities, limited vision, gross motor delays. It will be an outdoor learning space for the development of motor skills, turn taking, social skills and language development of all children who have the opportunity to use it.

We also know that this project will allow space for families with young children, who live in the surrounding east Lawrence neighborhoods to gather and interact with their young children in outdoor play, in an age appropriate inclusive playground after school hours and non-school days.

Want to be a part of this incredible project?
Purchase a brick or make a donation today!
www.LawrenceSchoolsFoundation.org
Kennedy Elementary School K-5 Lawrence Public Schools

post_text: As teachers and staff continue to prepare to connect with students, we’re smiling behind our masks!
shared_text:
Lawrence-Douglas County Public Health
August 19 at 4:30 PM ·

If I’m not sick, why should I wear a mask? New research shows around 50% of COVID cases could be from people that are infected but not showing symptoms yet (presymptomatic) or from people who are infected but do not get symptoms (asymptomatic). Masks protect others from respiratory droplets that contain saliva and mucus, which is the main way COVID is passed on. When everyone wears a mask, we all get the most protection. Read about the research https://bit.ly/2CezKPP and learn more about face masks: https://bit.ly/2OG4Q57
#DGKSCOVID

The school board will meet for a work session Monday at 5 p.m. with leaders from the Together Again: Fall 2020 Planning Task Force. This third task force update will include Remote learning plans for the start of school and safety measures planned for fall sports and activities. The district will follow KSHSAA and Sunflower League guidance on fall sports schedules. No board vote is planned Monday regarding athletics and activities.

At 6 p.m. the board will host its annual Public Budget Hearing. Community members may comment on the budget by emailing PatronCommentary@usd497.org to receive a link to the online meeting. The board will consider approving the 2020-2021 budget, which includes an increase of .497 mill from last year's tax rate, following the hearing. Review the agenda at www.usd497.org/SchoolBoard. Watch the meeting at www.usd497.org/Webstream.

post_text:
Please give us a minute to catch up! Due to increases in enrollment at the Lawrence Virtual School - LVS, the school district has suspended 2020-2021 LVS registration until current applications can be processed. LVS registration may reopen in the future if space permits. LVS is a charter school serving K-12 families from across the state of Kansas.

Lawrence Public Schools' brick-and-mortar schools will begin the school year September 8 with six weeks of remote learning. Families will also have an option for their children to continue learning remotely through Distance Learning whenever the district is able to transition to a Hybrid (On-Site/Remote) or In-Person model of instructional delivery. Families will receive more information about this option soon via email survey.

post_text:
The school board recognized the 2020 LMH Health Summer Leadership Academy participants: Kirk Johnson, Lawrence High; and Auna Childress, Fiona Swaggerty, and Thayu Kimori, Free State High.

“Inclusion, diversity, and equity should be woven into the fabric of who we are as an organization,” said Russ Johnson, president and CEO of LMH Health. “We want to help our community’s youth experience opportunities they may not know exist, and to experience them in a low-pressure environment where they can freely explore those options."

Superintendent Dr. Anthony Lewis said that providing paid internships to students from underrepresented groups is the kind of measurable action steps the district wants to see as a product of its equity work. “The benefits of this partnership with LMH Health extend beyond these students and their families to the community-at-large as we create a leadership development pipeline from our schools to the workforce,” he said.

(Photo credit: Gaskins Photography Collection. Courtesy LMH Health.)

There is no higher priority for us than the health and well-being of our staff, scholars, and school families. While the Governor’s Executive Order was not approved, we are preparing a proposal to begin the school year after Labor Day for the July 27 school board meeting. Our team has been working on calendar options since our July 13 board meeting at the direction of our school board. We will continue to work closely with our local health officials as they monitor health issues in our county impacting our staff and scholars.

#AllStudentsOneTeam

Douglas County is required to submit its plans for distributing the funding to the State of Kansas by Aug. 15 and the money needs to be spent by Dec. 30, 2020.

post_text:
We thank and congratulate Melissa Johnson, who on Monday will conclude her term as 2019-2020 president of the school board. The board chose Johnson in 2017 to fill a year-long vacancy. Voters then elected her to a four-year term in 2018. As a mother, educator, and veteran of the United States Marines, Johnson’s dedication to service is evident.

“As an educator, I strive to provide guidance that will equip scholars with the skills necessary to be successful human beings in their current and future endeavors. As a school board member, I can continue to do this work on a larger scale. I have the opportunity to help create policies and make budgetary decisions that promote equity, excellence, and engagement through our strategic plan,” said Johnson.

Thank you for your continued leadership, Melissa.

The school board meets at 6 p.m. Monday for its annual organizational meeting, including election of officers. The board will consider revising the 2020-2021 school calendar. Changes would move a staff professional development (PD) day from January 4 to August 11 and add a PD Day for middle school staff on February 12 so students at all grade levels are out of school that day.

The board will receive an initial report from the Together Again: Fall 2020 Planning Task Force. Since early June, more than 200 staff have served on working groups reviewing health and safety guidelines, discussing plans for reopening schools, and considering feedback from staff and school families. Survey results will be shared. Read about the task force's work at www.usd497.org/TogetherAgain.

Review the board agenda at www.usd497.org/SchoolBoard. For health and safety reasons, board meetings are being held online. Watch the meeting at www.usd497.org/Webstream or on Midco channel 26. Email PatronCommentary@usd497.org to receive a link to share public comments. Email written comments to schoolboard@usd497.org.

Congratulations to both Free State and Lawrence High Speech and Debate teams for completing a successful season! Due to the global pandemic, several national-qualifying preliminary rounds were canceled. 16 Lawrence Public Schools' students, a school-record 15 from Free State High and 1 from Lawrence High, were selected by the state to compete in the National Speech and Debate Association Virtual National Championship Tournament.

Lawrence Free State was recognized as a School of Excellence in Debate, an award given to the top 20 debate schools in the country for their debate performances at nationals. Nearly 1,400 schools competed in the tournament.

Kansas Governor Laura Kelly has appointed Superintendent Dr. Anthony Lewis to the Governor's Commission on Racial Equity and Justice. The commission studies issues of racial equity and justice in Kansas and will begin its work focusing on law enforcement-community relations. “As Governor, I am committed to ensuring this latest tragedy does not fade into the next news cycle. Communities of color do not have the luxury of time for leaders to address these issues,” Governor Laura Kelly said.

The Commission will hold listening sessions with Kansans across the state and make recommendations to the Governor, the Legislature, and local governments for concrete and immediate steps that can be taken to increase racial equity and justice in Kansas. Read more here: https://governor.kansas.gov/governor-laura-kelly-announces-commission-on-racial-equity-and-justice/

Superintendent Dr. Anthony Lewis presented the 2019-2020 Principal of the Year Awards, supported by Master LEAP partner Truity Credit Union, which presented $500 to each honoree. Dr. Lewis lauded Tammy Becker for her passion for caring for and meeting the individual needs of students. “Tammy has expertly guided her teachers and staff to create a homelike environment for students and a community center for school families. Staff
and parents work together as partners to support all students,” he said.

He shared that Kristen Ryan is hardworking, beloved by teachers and staff, and genuinely cares about the well-being of everyone on her team. “She puts students first and creates an environment where teachers feel comfortable taking risks and trying new solutions to meet student needs. Kristen makes her staff feel valued and respected,” said Dr. Lewis.

Congratulations to these two outstanding school leaders!

post_text: Starting tomorrow, viewers from around the world may stream a film by two Lawrence High seniors through the Smithsonian Learning Lab at s.si.edu/NHDShowcase2020. The National History Day documentary, “Alvin Ailey: Breaking Barriers in American Dance,” by Liliana Christensen and Zora Lotton-Barker will be part of an online showcase by the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture through June 24. The students' 10-minute documentary placed first at regional History Day competition, first at the virtual Kansas History Day competition, and is now one of 35 (out of 215) documentaries chosen for this national showcase. We're Chesty Lion proud of these two young historians!

post_text: Dr. Anthony Lewis shared in a message to school staff and families that as a Black man and father of two Black boys, and in his role as superintendent of more than 350 other Black boys, he takes personally the deaths of Black men at the hands of law enforcement and the social injustice and systemic racism that permeate the societal fabric of our nation. "Walking alongside some of our scholars during the recent Downtown Lawrence protest march and seeing the hurt, concern, and uncertainty on their faces saddened me. They deserve better," he said. Dr. Lewis urges each member of our school community to examine personal bias, speak out against social injustices, and stand up for and learn from others who do not look like us. "This urgent work starts with each of us. Lawrence can lead the way...We must continue to eliminate behaviors, policies, practices, and procedures that perpetuate systemic racism," he said. Read the superintendent's message and learn more about the school district's racial equity work at www.usd497.org/equity. #AllStudentsOneTeam

Due to the Memorial Day holiday, the Lawrence Board of Education will meet (online) at 6 p.m. Tuesday, May 26. The board will hear two annual reports about technology and communications.

The district’s Learning Forward/Future Ready initiative commits to equipping every student with the technology needed to learn and communicate in the 21st century. The technology report will include how the district has addressed changes to teaching and learning as a result of COVID-19. The Communications Team will update the board on its charge to build awareness of, and engage the school community in, the district's work to achieve the goals of the strategic plan.

Review the school board’s agenda at www.usd497.org/SchoolBoard. Watch the board meeting at www.usd497.org/Webstream or on Midco channel 26. If you would like to address the board during the meeting, please email PublicCommentary@usd497.org prior to the Public Commentary period of the agenda to receive a link to join the online meeting.

Did you know that Lawrence Public Schools provides a Pre-K Readiness and Peer Mentoring Program?

Children who are four by August 31, 2020, live within district boundaries, and meet qualifications are eligible for the free Pre-K Readiness Program. Review the qualifications at www.usd497.org/EarlyChildhoodPrograms.

Register your child for the Pre-K Readiness Program at www.usd497.org/NewStudentRegistration.

The Peer Model program provides students with rich learning opportunities for growth in pre-academics, language, and social skills in an inclusive preschool classroom. Peer models develop friendships with children who demonstrate a diverse range of developmental skills and abilities.
Contact Marielle at MMonteau@usd497.org or 785-330-1985 for information or to schedule a screening.

Follow Lawrence Public Schools Early Childhood Program for activities, story time, and more!

post_text: This Saturday, May 16, at 8 p.m. Eastern, former President Barack Obama will deliver a commencement address to graduating seniors nationwide as part of an hour-long multimedia Graduate Together: America Honors the High School Class of 2020 event. This program will be aired simultaneously Saturday evening by more than 20 broadcast TV (ABC, CBS, FOX, and NBC) and digital streaming partners. Joining Obama will be NBA star and school founder LeBron James, Nobel Prize winner Malala Yousafzai, the Jonas Brothers and soccer superstar Megan Rapinoe, among others. The event will feature highlights from thousands of student submissions, a collection of commencement addresses, celebrity performances and inspirational vignettes. Learn more about this event here https://graduatetogether2020.com.

post_text:
The Lawrence Schools Foundation “Zoom bombed” a Quail Run Elementary School online staff meeting today. A doorbell rang at one of the staff member’s homes. Kaitlin Shulman, second grade teacher, opened the door to receive The Bobs Award and a $10,000 check in front of cheering family and friends gathered on the sidewalk.

Every spring the Foundation presents to an outstanding teacher this award donated by generous community members named Bob. A parent wrote of Shulman, “My son comes home each and every day telling me about their lessons. His thirst for constant knowledge is something that is new this year. I truly believe his ongoing desire to learn is a testament to their lessons and his teacher’s love for teaching.”

Congratulations, Kaitlin Shulman, and our thanks to the Foundation and the Bobs!

post_text: We’ve gathered ideas from students, parents, staff, and other school districts during our planning for the Apollo Kansans Can School Redesign Project sponsored by the Kansas State Department of Education. It’s time now to hear from our teams at Broken Arrow, Deerfield, Hillcrest and Free State High and see what they have in mind for the launch of implementation in the fall. Each school’s team will present its redesign plan during Monday’s online school board meeting at 6 p.m. Watch the livestream at www.usd497.org/webstream.

post_text: Student musicians: KU’s Midwestern Music Camp is going virtual, and it’s free!
shared_text:
Midwestern Music Camp
May 5 at 3:10 PM ·

The tradition continues - the Midwestern Music Camp is proud to announce our VIRTUAL camp for this summer!

A variety of content will be offered via pre-recorded material and live sessions via Zoom. Thanks to the generous support of the Meyer Music and the Band of Angels program, the camp is FREE!

Instructors include applied faculty from The University of Kansas, and we will have several special guest artists joining us!

The first 500 campers to complete the camp will receive a free t-shirt and sticker in the mail. The camp is open to students entering 7th grade through graduating high school seniors, nationwide!

Parents may also register their students for a private lesson on their instrument for an additional fee.

For more information, please visit: http://music.ku.edu/mmc

post_text:
Our teachers change the lives of children every day—their immense work and impact moves the rest of us beyond words. With the abrupt end to the physical school year, teachers have done even more to continue education with e-learning and at-home lessons. They are ensuring that every student has the tools they need to reach their full potential. This week, we hope that teachers are showered with appreciation and love for the pivotal role they play in the life of children, families, and our community, and for inspiring a lifelong love of learning!

To celebrate, Lawrence Public Schools Instagram Page will post teacher appreciation videos all week on our story. If you'd like to shout out your teachers, post a video on your Instagram and tag @usd497 on the video and we will add you to the story.

post_text: The Lawrence Board of Education on Monday approved an amended 2020-2021 School Calendar to correspond to the phase four completion date outlined in the construction contract for Lawrence High School. The changes only affect our high schools. High school staff will return August 17-19 for professional development, planning, and a workday. A half-day ninth grade orientation will take place August 20. High school classes will begin August 21. Find next year's school calendar at www.usd497.org/calendar2020-2021.

A half-day ninth grade orientation will take place August 20. High school classes will begin August 21. Find next year's school calendar at www.usd497.org/calendar2020-2021.

post_text: Congratulations to ACE Award winner Michelle Barnes, Woodlawn parent involvement facilitator. Thank you to the Lawrence Schools Foundation for honoring outstanding staff.
shared_text:
Lawrence Schools Foundation
April 28 at 2:27 AM ·

Congrats to Spring A.C.E Award recipient, Michelle Barnes!

Michelle, a Parent Facilitator-Title 1 with Woodlawn Elementary, was presented the award and a $500 cash gift, during a surprise Zoom presentation & staff meeting this afternoon!

“She helps students understand not only the importance of school but also the importance of being a good human being.” commented Jayci Roberson, Woodlawn Elementary Principal.

When asked about Michelle for this award, a peer stated, “I don’t know that I’ve ever worked at a school that had a “Michelle”, someone who is universally there for students, staff, administration, and families alike. She fills so many roles for us and I can’t imagine Woodlawn without her.”

Lawrence Schools Foundation A.C.E. Award (Acknowledging Classified Employees)
Recognizes and applauds classified employees whose efforts benefit students, faculty and staff, and others within and outside the USD 497 community.

Congrats to Michelle Barnes!
Lawrence Public Schools
#RiseLawrence

post_text: Kansas Teachers of the Year will bring educational programs to children of all ages on local PBS television stations, beginnng Monday. Click the link for TV schedules.
shared_text:
Kansas State Department of Education
April 17 at 9:46 PM ·

We are excited to announce that Kansas teachers, students and parents just got a new partner in their continuous learning efforts.

Thanks to the support of Kansas Public Broadcasters, Kansas students will receive supplemental education content by way of a new television program produced by Kansas PBS stations and KSDE, and hosted by local teachers. The new program called Learning Across Kansas will begin airing the week of April 20.

Each 30-minute segment, individually produced for elementary, middle school and high school students, will feature grade-specific educational content delivered by our very own Kansas teachers who serve on KSDE’s Continuous Learning Task Force.

Teachers, students and parents/caregivers, tune in for short, fun and engaging lessons. Plus, you just might see one of your own teachers presenting!

Learn more by visiting, https://www.ksde.org/Agency/Fiscal-and-Administrative-Services/Communications-and-Recognition-Programs/Learning-Across-Kansas

post_text:
Governor Laura Kelly and Department for Children and Families Secretary Laura Howard announced that DCF will begin issuing an emergency food assistance benefit to CURRENT program households. The emergency allotment increases a household’s monthly benefit to the maximum allowed for the size of the family. The maximum monthly benefit for a family of four is $646.

If you currently receive these funds no additional application is necessary to receive the emergency funds. Families should start to see their March emergency benefit on their EBT card beginning April 15. The distribution will follow the standard alphabetical schedule. DCF will distribute April emergency benefits in mid to late May.

Households that already receive the maximum monthly allotment are NOT eligible for emergency assistance. The allotment is for March and April only.

Those interested in applying for food assistance can visit the DCF website at www.dcf.ks.gov. For more information on COVID-19 visit: www.kdheks.gov/coronavirus.

post_text: Boys & Girls Club of Lawrence provides FREE online opportunities for all school-age children to learn and have fun! No membership required.
shared_text:
Boys & Girls Club of Lawrence
April 16 at 8:28 PM ·

You don't have to be a member of the Boys & Girls Club to need a place to turn to. You don't have to stay in Boys & Girls Club when this pandemic has passed. Right now, we are here for your children. We are all embracing a new normal and learning how to stay #ApartTogether.

post_text:
The school board approved a Neighborhood Revitalization Act Project for the Penn Street Lofts tonight. The city and county commissions also will consider this recommendation from the Public Incentives Review Committee.

After two years of study, the board approved the expansion of AVID, a college and career readiness system designed to improve learning schoolwide. The four elementary schools that provide English as a Second Language services -- Cordley, Hillcrest, Schwegler, and Sunflower -- will implement AVID in 2020-2021. Kennedy Elementary will take a year to monitor and plan for its potential launch of AVID the following year. All four middle schools and both high schools already participate in AVID.

In order to facilitate timely decision-making during the pandemic, the board and the Lawrence Education Association entered into a Memorandum of Understanding that gives a negotiations subcommittee the power to make changes to the Master Agreement. Any changes made under the MOU sunset at the end of the current school year.

shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
How to Make Your own Face Covering

Lawrence-Douglas County Public Health
April 4 at 5:39 PM ·

CDC RECOMMENDATIONS ON CLOTH FACE COVERINGS
The coronavirus can spread between people interacting in close proximity — for example, speaking, coughing, or sneezing — even if those people are not exhibiting symptoms. In light of this new evidence, CDC recommends wearing cloth face coverings in public settings where other social distancing measures are difficult to maintain (e.g., grocery stores and pharmacies) especially in areas of significant community-based transmission. https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/cloth-face-cover.html

It is critical to emphasize that maintaining six-feet social distancing remains important to slowing the spread of the virus. The cloth face coverings recommended ARE NOT surgical masks or N-95 respirators. Those are critical supplies that must continue to be reserved for healthcare workers and other medical first responders, as recommended by current CDC guidance.

How to Make Your own Face Covering:
https://youtu.be/tPx1yqvJgf4

post_text:
Inspired by local chalk drawings around town, Southwest Middle School Advancement via Individual Determination, or AVID, teacher Barbara Nitz set out to draw one of her own. Using tape, chalk, and some help from her husband, they created a chalk mosaic drawing honoring AVID.

Neighbors inquired from the sidewalk about AVID and why she was drawing. "It was a fantastic tool for me to educate people about what AVID is and how awesome my students are! The next thing I know, people are driving by, stopping, and taking pictures of it," said Nitz.

One of the neighbors stopping by to take photos with the drawing was one of Nitz's students. They posted the photo in Nitz's Google Classroom. Students saw the photo and went to take one of their own. Since Monday, students in Nitz's class have stopped by for their photo with the art. They share their photos in their Google classroom so their classmates can see. What a special way to connect!

post_text:
To assist 2020 high school seniors during the extended school closure ordered by the Governor, the school board unanimously approved reducing the current graduation requirements (23 credits) to the 21 credits required by the Kansas State Department of Education for graduation.

The change does not alter the number of core course requirements – English language arts (4), social studies (3), science (3), math (3), physical education (1), and fine arts (1). The difference is in two fewer electives required for graduation. The change sunsets at the end of the 2019-2020 school year.

Seniors must complete any core courses they are taking now. Staff will conference with the families of any current juniors who have already met the graduation requirements.

Board President Melissa Johnson opened the meeting by thanking district staff, students, and families for their adherence to public health guidelines and their kindness in helping others during this difficult and uncertain time.

post_text: The Kansas State Department of Education has now recommended that all Kansas schools close next week. Lawrence Public Schools has already closed through March 29 by order of Lawrence-Douglas County Public Health to prevent the spread of COVID-19. Please stay home and limit social contact.
shared_text:
Kansas State Department of Education
March 15 at 9:32 PM ·

As of Sunday, March 15, Kansas Education Commissioner Dr. Randy Watson strongly recommends that those schools currently coming off of spring break, suspend operations for the week March 16-20. All schools scheduled for spring break the week of March 16-20 will continue as planned. For schools who have spring break later in time, Commissioner Watson is strongly recommending they also close schools for the period of March 16-20.

Closing all schools during this same period of time provides Kansas officials the time needed to finalize a comprehensive plan for how to address COVID-19.

It is critical that we all follow a coordinated response to this situation

post_text: Smiles and laughter filled the Sunset Hill library as Savannah Franz's fifth graders and Nicole Corn's kindergartners came together for a fun project. Each year, fifth grade students are paired with kindergarten "buddies." These pairs play games, read books, and teach each other skills. Fifth graders picked a picture book to read and created a board game based off of the book for their buddies. Our kindergartners beamed as their buddies read to them and taught them how to play their personalized games.

post_text: It's a great day to be a Sunset Hill Elementary Eagle! Fifth grade students created board games based on picture books for their kindergarten buddies. The older students read their books to their buddies and then played their games together. Today's library visit focused on the letter "U" for our kindergartners. Our students found the letter "U" in their find-a-letter work page and learned the letter "U" and the word understand in sign language. While completing their find-a-letter work page, this student danced and sang his favorite song, "Brick House" by the Commodores, because it has the letter "U" in the title. What a smart connection and fantastic way to start a Wednesday!

post_text: School board members and district administrators enjoyed a great lunch and visit with the young adults and staff of the Community Transition Program last week at East Heights. C-Tran participants guided their guests on tours of their recently renovated classrooms, a workroom, where they sort donations of clothing and shoes; an apartment space, where they practice independent living skills; and the district Clothing Closet that they neatly organize for students in need of items. At C-Tran, high school graduates ages 18-21 gain vocational, work experience, and self-care skills; and learn functional academic instruction. Contact 785-330-4906 to schedule a donation drop-off of new or clean, gently worn items or shoes for the district Clothing Closet.

Guess whose U.S. History class already knew about Census 2020 when the crew arrived to film in their classroom? Dave Olson's students at Billy Mills Middle School! Did you know that invitations to participate in the Census will be sent to all Douglas County residents between March 12-20?

The Census asks 10 questions. It takes 10 minutes to complete. Everyone counts! Census data is used to distribute $6 billion in federal funds every year in Kansas, including funding especially important to us for school lunch programs, Title reading and math programs, career and technical education grants, and support for the Individuals with Disabilities Act. Learn more at www.lawrence.org/Census and be counted!

post_text: The Lawrence Board of Education’s legislative priorities support anti-vaping initiatives and raising the age for purchase and possession of tobacco and nicotine products to 21 (Tobacco 21 proposals) for the health and well-being of our youth.

February 13 at 3:10 PM ·

HB 2563 - Prohibits the use of cigarette, electronic cigarettes, consumable material and tobacco products in any school building. Also amends the law to prohibit selling electronic cigarettes containing flavored materials except for menthol flavored consumable material to anyone under 21 and amends the criminal statutes to include selling and using electronic cigarettes to those under 21.

post_text: Did you know that the largest apprenticeship program in Kansas is in Lawrence? It's the Dwayne Peaslee Technical Training Center. School board members and district administrators toured Peaslee Tech, 2920 Haskell Ave., on Tuesday to learn more about the adult technical training center. The district partners with Peaslee Tech for the College & Career Center's welding and automotive classes. It also is home to the district's Adult Learning Center's adult basic education, ESL services, and GED study and testing programs. Peaslee Tech offers online and on campus courses, including classes through affiliated colleges. Among its other technical training offerings are commercial driver's licensing, court reporting, industrial maintenance, pharmacy tech, and residential electric, plumbing, and HVAC programs.

post_text: What do potassium permanganate, reading music, the macarena, and Sam Cooke all have in common? They were all mentioned in Liberty Memorial Central Middle School classrooms today! Josh Spradlin's science class mixed hydrogen peroxide, soap, and potassium permanganate together to observe the reaction and gauge temperature. Mandana Hurt's eighth graders stopped measuring light and broke out in the Macarena to give their brains a short break. October Davis' flex class continued their weekly short research project featuring black historical figures by researching famous black musicians, like Samuel Cook. They are using Black History Month to tie their year-long discussion about black historical figures together. Christopher Kurt's sixth grade music class demonstrated their knowledge of rhythm and reading music by recording themselves clapping on beat to a piece of short music. Our mustangs are always learning!

post_text: Billy Mills Middle School's seventh grade AVID class visited Kennedy Elementary School K-5 to work with each class on a Black History Month project. Middle schoolers taught the elementary students about the historical significance of quilting for the underground railroad. Students provided the most common patterns used for wayfinding and explained what message each pattern communicated. Everyone colored tiles to make their own patterns and mini quilt. Smiles shined in each classroom as the multi-age project commenced.

Lied Center of Kansas - Performing Arts Center
February 7 at 5:29 PM ·

Last but not least in the Ovation! USD 497 Talent Show lineup...Ben Willems, 8th grader at Southwest Middle School, on drums! Ben started playing drums when he was five years old and has also studied piano for six years. He is principal player of the 8th grade percussionists in band at SWMS, and he loves the variety of instruments that being a percussionist allows him to play. He was chosen for the John Phillip Sousa Honor Band this year and has been accepted into the All‐City Jazz Band for the last three years. He also enjoyed participating in the Midwestern Music Camp for the past two summers. We can’t wait to hear him play!

January 22 at 2:45 PM ·

The census is coming! The census is coming!

Look for the census in your mailbox this March. After you receive your census, it only takes a few minutes to complete (and can be completed online, by mail or over the phone).

After you complete the census, share your participation with friends, family, neighbors and colleagues–your assurance might encourage others to participate in the 2020 Census who may not otherwise plan to do so. Visit kansascounts.org for more information. #KansasCounts #2020Census

post_text: The Thomas John Giffin Foundation provided tiny-k Early Intervention a $7,500 donation made possible by the annual TJ5K & Family Fun Run in November. Tiny-k Early Intervention provides services to support families of children from birth to age three who have a diagnosed or potential delay or disability. The Giffin family were participants in tiny-k. The Foundation, named after their son who passed away at 21 months of age from undetermined causes, continues to give back to the program each year. The TJ5K & Family Fun Run was initiated in 2013 and has raised more than $32,500 for tiny-k!

Tiny-k Early Intervention provides services to support families of children from birth to age three who have a diagnosed or potential delay or disability. Reminder: No school Monday, January 20. Please join us for New York Elementary School’s annual Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Chili Feed 5-7 p.m. Tuesday, January 21, at the school. They will serve meat and vegetarian chili, sides, drinks, and dessert. A free will donation will be collected at the door. This is a community event, and all are welcome!

We also invite the public to attend USD 497’s ONE DREAM MLK Celebration Thursday, January 23, at Billy Mills Middle School. A gallery of interactive exhibits opens at 5:30 p.m. The program starts at 6:30 p.m. and features student cultural tributes and performances and the presentation of the MLK Awards to deserving students, staff, and community members. Refreshments served.

post_text:
Students competed today in Dewey, Oklahoma at the Battle of the Plains Powwow contest. Dancers representing Lawrence Public Schools' Native American Student Services from left to right include Lucas Crow Eagle (7th grade, Liberty Memorial Central Middle School), Shelby Bointy (10th grade, Lawrence High School), Sara Bointy (8th grade, Billy Mills Middle School), Amaya Harris (11th grade, Lawrence High School), Evelyn LeBeau (10th grade, Free State High School), and Misun Antoine (5th grade, Pinckney Elementary). The group’s sponsor is LMCMS staff member Shelley Bointy. Good luck to our students as they compete today!

Since 1972, the Native American Student Services (NASS) program has provided educational opportunities and support for American Indian/Alaska Native children in the Lawrence Public Schools. The goal of NASS is to enhance and provide support to the students’ overall growth and development through cultural and academic programs for students and families. Jennifer Attocknie serves as the coordinator of NASS.
